F(9) = 34
F(10) = 55
F(11) = 89
F(12) = 144
F(13) = 233
F(14) = 377
```

## How It Works

The Fibonacci sequence is defined as:
```
F(0) = 0
F(1) = 1
F(n) = F(n-1) + F(n-2)  for n > 1
```

### Recursion Tree for `fibonacci(5)`:

```
                    fib(5)
                  /        \
             fib(4)        fib(3)
            /      \       /     \
        fib(3)   fib(2)  fib(2)  fib(1)
        /   \    /   \    /   \      |
    fib(2) fib(1) fib(1) fib(0) fib(1) fib(0)  1
    /   \    |     |      |      |      |
fib(1) fib(0) 1   1      0      1      0
  |      |
  1      0
```

## Key Points

| Aspect | Detail |
|--------|--------|
| **Base Cases** | `F(0) = 0` and `F(1) = 1` |
| **Recursive Case** | `F(n) = F(n-1) + F(n-2)` |
| **Time Complexity** | **O(2ⁿ)** — exponential (many repeated calculations) |
| **Space Complexity** | **O(n)** — due to recursion stack depth |

## ⚠️ Limitation & Optimized Version

The simple recursive approach is **inefficient** for large `n` due to repeated calculations. Here's an **optimized version using memoization**:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <map>
using namespace std;

map<int, long long> memo;

long long fibonacci(int n) {
    if (n <= 0) return 0;
    if (n == 1) return 1;

    // Check if already computed
    if (memo.find(n) != memo.end())
        return memo[n];

    // Store result before returning
    memo[n] = fibonacci(n - 1) + fibonacci(n - 2);
    return memo[n];
}

int main() {
    int n;
    cout << "Enter n: ";
    cin >> n;
    cout << "F(" << n << ") = " << fibonacci(n) << endl;
    return 0;
}
```

> **Memoization** reduces the time complexity from **O(2ⁿ)** to **O(n)** by storing previously computed results and avoiding redundant calculations.

